{
  "doc_id": "22187",
  "text": "While it has been found that children with CIs can have difficulty discriminating between /s/ and /$/, it is not the case that these two phonemes are indistinguishable to individuals who use CIs. [CITATION_1] found a wide range of performance by children and adults with CIs in discriminating between /s/ and /$/, and also found that children who had used their implants longer had better discrimination performance. Furthermore, studies on phoneme identification by high-performing adults with CIs have shown that perceptual confusions between /s/ and /$/ are relatively uncommon [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . These findings suggest that at least for some individuals, CIs provide sufficient acoustic information for them to discriminate between /s/ and /$/. This is consistent with the findings that differences are apparent in the electrode output of the Ineraid cochlear implant between the sounds /s/ and /$/ as produced by an adult female speaker [CITATION_4] .",
